    <title>Combined summary - Memory leaks?</title>
    <updated>2023-06-11T00:11:28.164300+00:00</updated>
    <link href="https://lists.linuxfoundation.org/pipermail/bitcoin-dev/2015-October/011559.html" rel="alternate"/>
    <summary>In October 2015, concerns were raised by Jonathan Toomim and other members of the Bitcoin community about anomalous memory usage scaling. They reported that several running bitcoind processes were using over 3GB of RAM despite mempool seeming to be under control. The issue appeared to happen with both Bitcoin Core 0.10.1 and Bitcoin XT 0.11B. Possible explanations for the effect include leaks, caches, and fragmentation. Debugging tools were not ideal to investigate the issue, but a build with tcmalloc may be useful in investigating heap statistics.Valgrind did not reveal any promising results, but the mempool growth can be mitigated by setting `-mintxfee`. One user suggested using a build with tcmalloc to investigate heap statistics. There were also concerns about misleading information from tools like top when measuring memory usage on Linux. To measure memory usage accurately on Linux, Tom Zander shared his script for providing Virtual Resident Set Size (VmRSS) values.The conversation has since moved to an issue on Github to keep it organized. Users shared their experiences with the memory usage issue and suggested solutions such as adding a cron job to restart bitcoind every day or two as a damage control mechanism until the issue is resolved. Some users emphasized the need to measure memory usage correctly on Linux using scripts provided by Tom Zander. Btc Drak suggested that the conversation should move to an issue on Github to keep it focused and organized, and one user opened an issue on Github for the topic in question.In October 2015, Jonathan Toomim reported excessive memory usage on several machines running Debian and p2pool with either Bitcoin Core or XT. After restarting the processes, the mempool size and RAM usage decreased significantly. Toomim asked for guesses on where the memory leak might be or what was using the additional 2.4 GB of memory. Other users on the bitcoin-dev mailing list also reported similar issues with high memory usage, leading to speculation that it may be related to CreateNewBlock() and getblocktemplate.The Bitcoin community has been discussing a potential memory leak issue related to the bitcoind process. Multipool Admin reported that the bitcoind process was getting killed every few days when it reached approximately 55 GB of usage on their server and suggested adding a cron job to restart bitcoind every day or two until the issue was resolved. The email thread discusses various attempts to mitigate the mempool growth and investigate the cause of high memory usage in Bitcoin nodes.In response to Mr. Hearn's threats to "ban people" based on their preferences, suggestions, or characterizations of his chosen software project, another member stated that he doesn't own the list and has very little to say on this matter at this stage.Some users also experienced the memory usage issue on Linux but not on Mac OS X under a GBT workload, suggesting that it may be a fragmentation issue due to poor memory allocation or bloated caches. One developer experienced high memory usage on a running bitcoind process, and others reported similar issues on both Linux and Mac OS X. An investigation into the issue found that the getblocktemplate RPC may be implicated in the problem, but valgrind did not show any signs of a multi-GB leak.The email thread discusses several possible solutions to mitigate the mempool growth, such as setting `-mintxfee`. Tom Zander shared a Linux command to measure memory usage more accurately. The group suggests measuring memory usage correctly on Linux using scripts like "showmemusage" and warns against trolling behavior.</summary>
